[0m  [2m--- README ---
[0m  [2m     1	# ETL Log Report
[0m  [2m     2	
[0m  [2m     3	This project reads an application log, extracts structured events, simulates loading them to a database, and writes `report.html` with the same report format used before.
[0m  [2m     4	
[0m  [2m     5	## Configuration
[0m  [2m     6	
[0m  [2m     7	The script now reads configuration from environment variables instead of hardcoded values:
[0m  [2m     8	
[0m  [2m     9	- `ETL_DB_HOST` (default: `localhost`)
[0m  [2m    10	- `ETL_DB_USER` (default: `admin`)
[0m  [2m    11	- `ETL_DB_PASSWORD` (default: `password123`)
[0m  [2m    12	- `ETL_LOG_FILE` (default: `server.log`)
[0m  [2m    13	- `ETL_REPORT_FILE` (default: `report.html`)
[0m  [2m    14	
[0m  [2m    15	## Usage
[0m  [2m    16	
[0m  [2m    17	```bash
[0m  [2m    18	python3 etl.py
[0m  [2m    19	```
[0m  [2m    20	
[0m  [2m    21	Example with custom configuration:
[0m  [2m    22	
[0m  [2m    23	```bash
[0m  [2m    24	ETL_DB_HOST=db.internal \
[0m  [2m    25	ETL_DB_USER=reporter \
[0m  [2m    26	ETL_DB_PASSWORD=secret \
[0m  [2m    27	python3 etl.py
[0m  [2m    28	```
[0m  [2m    29	
[0m  [2m    30	## Notes
[0m  [2m    31	
[0m  [2m    32	- Parsing is whitespace-tolerant for supported log lines.
[0m  [2m    33	- The generated `report.html` structure is preserved.
[0m  [2m    34	- A sample log file is created automatically if the configured log file does not exist.
[0m  [2m    35	
